    <p>NPR's Soraya Sarhaddi Nelson is in the capital, Khartoum, and she reports that the government's plan has the millions of Christians who live in the North fearing for the future. </p>
    <p>(Soundbite of singing) </p>
    <p>SORAYA SARHADDI NELSON: Two Christian women in this slum outside Khartoum sing that Jesus will protect and guide them as they travel south. For the women and thousands of others here in Jabarona who wait outside with their belongings, the trip can't come fast enough. </p>
    <p>(Soundbite of arguments) </p>
    <p>NELSON: Arguments erupt over whose belongings are loaded first. Everyone seems to fear being left behind. </p>
    <p>Mr. JOSEPH YEL: (Foreign language spoken) </p>
