    <p>Ms. JANICE FEDARCYK (FBI Agent): The vow of silence that is part of the oath ofOmertais more myth than reality today. </p>
    <p>SMITH: And with all these guys singing like canaries, the FBI was helped out by a little technology. </p>
    <p>Ms. FEDARCYK: Dozens of court-authorized wiretaps allowed us to listen in on phone calls, and thousands of conversations were recorded by cooperators. </p>
    <p>SMITH: All the profanity-laden threats and boasts that fill these pages will mean plenty of interesting reading tonight for buffs of organized crime. Today's indictments are a reminder, Holder says, that the mob is still around, still dangerous, still sucking money from businesses. </p>
    <p>Mr. HOLDER: I think the mob certainly has been weakened. It is different from what it was once before, but the reality is it is an ongoing threat, a major threat to the economic well-being of this country, in addition to being the violent organization that it is and therefore deserving of our attention. </p>
